        <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Construction-of-rhombus">
            <title>Construction of a rhombus</title>
            <p>
                Follow the instruction below and construct a rhombus.
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Instructions</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul> 
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select <term>point tool(Window 1),</term> create points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> on the applet.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    
                    <li>
                        <p>
                             Select <term>compass tool(Window 3)</term>. Then click on point <m>A</m> and point <m>B</m> 
                             and again on point <m>A</m> to construct a circle. 
                             Then click on <m>B</m> and <m>A</m> again on <m>B</m> to construct another circle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Select <term>intersect tool(Window 5),</term> click on the two circles to mark the point of intersection of the circles  
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select <term>segment tool(Window 6),</term> and draw  line segments <m>AD, DB. BC \text{ and } CA</m> 
                            to construct a rhombus.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Hide the circles by selecting the <term>show/hide object tool(Window 8)</term> and then click on the circles.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select the <term>angle tool(Window)</term> and measure  in the rhombus angles
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select <term>move tool(Window 7)</term> and move points <m>A</m> or <m>B</m> and observe what happens to your rhombus. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    
                </ul>
            </p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Rhombus</caption>
                <interactive xml:id="geogebra-rhombus" platform="geogebra" width="95%" aspect="4:3">
                <slate xml:id="Rhombus" surface="geogebra" material="tfsuycqc" aspect="4:3">
                    enableShiftDragZoom(true);
                    showResetIcon(true);
                </slate>
                </interactive>
            </figure>
            
        </subsubsection>

        <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Construction-of-irregular-pentagon">
            <title>Construction of irregular pentagon</title>
            <p>
                Construct an irregular hexagon using the following instructions.
                 You have been provided with a segment <m>AB</m> measuring <m>8 cm.</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Instructions</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Measure <m>\angle 120^\circ</m> at <m>B</m> by selecting on the <term>Angle with given size tool(Window 3),</term>
                            then click on point <m>A</m> and <m>B.</m>  On the pop-up window, input angle size as <m>120^\circ</m> and 
                            click on <term>clockwise</term> then <term>OK.</term> This will construct an angle <m>ABA'.</m> Select on the <term>
                            line tool(Window 6)</term> to construct a line through <m>BA'.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Select on the <term>circle with given radius tool(Window 8).</term> Click on point <m>B</m> and on the pop-up window, 
                            input the radius as <m>8</m> then click <term>OK.</term> This creates a circle with centre <m>B</m> and radis <m>8 cm.</m>
                             Select the <term>intersect tool(Window 7)</term> and click at the point of intersection <term>C</term> of the circle with the
                              line <m>BA'.</m> The distance <m>BC</m> measures <m>8 cm</m> which is the radius of the circle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Measure an angle <m>140^\circ</m> at <m>C</m> by selecting on the <term>Angle with given size tool(Window 3),</term>
                            then click on point <m>B</m> and <m>C.</m>  On the pop-up window, input angle size as <m>140^\circ</m> and 
                            click on <term>clockwise</term> then <term>OK.</term> This will construct an angle <m>BCB'.</m> Select on the <term>
                            line tool(Window 6)</term> to construct a line through <m>CB'.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select on the <term>circle with given radius tool(Window 8).</term> Click on point <m>C</m> and on the pop-up window, 
                            input the radius as <m>5</m> then click <term>OK.</term> This creates a circle with centre <m>C</m> and radis <m>5 cm.</m>
                             Select the <term>intersect tool(Window 7)</term> and click at the point of intersection <term>D</term> of the circle with the
                              line <m>CB'.</m> The distance <m>CD</m> measures <m>5 cm</m> which is the radius of the circle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Measure <m>\angle 110^\circ</m> at <m>A</m> by selecting on the <term>Angle with given size tool(Window 3),</term>
                            then click on point <m>B</m> and <m>A.</m>  On the pop-up window, input angle size as <m>110^\circ</m> and 
                            click on <term>counterclockwise</term> then <term>OK.</term> This will construct an angle <m>BAB'_{1}.</m> Select on the <term>
                            line tool(Window 6)</term> to construct a line through <m>AB'_{1}.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select on the <term>circle with given radius tool(Window 8).</term> Click on point <m>A</m> and on the pop-up window, 
                            input the radius as <m>7</m> then click <term>OK.</term> This creates a circle with centre <m>A</m> and radis <m>7 cm.</m>
                             Select the <term>intersect tool(Window 7)</term> and click at the point of intersection <term>E</term> of the circle with the
                              line <m>AB'_{1}.</m> The distance <m>AE</m> measures <m>7 cm</m> which is the radius of the circle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           select the <term>hide/show label tool (Window 9)</term> and click on the lines <m>AB, BA', CB' \text{ and } AB'_{1}</m> to hide 
                            the lines. Also click on the points <m>A', B' \text{ and }B'_{1}</m> to hide them.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select on the <term>segment tool(Window 2)</term> and draw segments <m>AB, BC,BD,DE \text{ and } EA</m> to form an irregular pentagon.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select on <term>angle tool(Window 5)</term> and click on points <m>E, D, C</m> to measure the size of <m>\angle EDC.</m>
                             Click on points <m>A, E, D</m> to measure the size of <m>\angle AED.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Right click on the segments and click on settings. Then click on  <term>Show label</term> and on the drop down arrow select <term>Value.</term>
                             This will display the length of the segment. Repeat this to all the other segments in your pentagon.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <p>
                What is the measure of <m>DE, EA, \angle AED \text{ and } \angle EDC.</m> Share your findings with other learners.
            </p>

